AU  - Nickell, Stephen
T1  - The Determinants of Occupational Success in Britain
PY  - 1982
Y1  - 1982/01/01
DO  - 10.2307/2297139
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 49
IS  - 1
SP  - 43
EP  - 53
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - This paper is concerned with measuring the true impact of certain human capital variables on an individual's occupational position. The particular variables which are analysed are training, qualifications and spells of sickness and unemployment. The longitudinal nature of the data enables us to control for all relevant individual attributes which remain fixed over the period of the sample. This is vitally important because these attributes are strongly correlated with the variables of interest and would seriously corrupt estimates derived from a single cross-section. A method of generating consistent estimates (as N → ∞, T fixed) for a dynamic model with fixed effects is also illustrated.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/2297139
ER  - 



